    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Numbers 11-19 & Noun Agreement",
      "explanation": "Numbers 11-19 are formed by combining the unit with 'naest' (short for 'na deset' - on ten): jedanaest (11), dvanaest (12), trinaest (13), četrnaest (14), petnaest (15), šesnaest (16), sedamnaest (17), osamnaest (18), devetnaest (19). In Croatian, the number 'one' (jedan/jedna/jedno) changes to match the gender of the noun it modifies, while numbers 2-4 require a special plural form and numbers 5+ use the genitive plural.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "Eleven",
          "target_primary": "Jedanaest",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Fifteen",
          "target_primary": "Petnaest",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "One man (masculine)",
          "target_primary": "Jedan čovjek",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "One woman (feminine)",
          "target_primary": "Jedna žena",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Five people",
          "target_primary": "Pet ljudi",
          "target_alt": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Currency in Croatia",
      "content": "As of January 1, 2023, Croatia adopted the Euro as its official currency, replacing the Croatian Kuna (HRK) which had been in use since 1994. You may still hear older Croatians refer to prices in kunas out of habit. Croatia also joined the Schengen Area on the same date, making border crossings with neighboring EU countries seamless. When discussing prices, Croatians commonly say 'eura' (genitive plural) after numbers 5 and above, e.g., 'deset eura' (ten euros)."
    }
